solution.p:
Using the chain rule:
y(t)&=f(x(t))
\diff{y}{t}=\diff{}{t}\left\{f(x(t))\right\}&=\diff{f}{x}\cdot\diff{x}{t}
\mbox{so, }\qquad\diff{f}{x}&=\diff{y}{t}\div \diff{x}{t}
Using y(t)=\cos^2 t and x(t)=\sin t: \diff{f}{x}&=\left(-2\cos t \sin t \right)\div\left( \cos t \right)=-2\sin t=-2x
So, when t=\dfrac{10\pi}{3} and x=-\dfrac{\sqrt{3}}{2}, \diff{f}{x}\left(\dfrac{-\sqrt{3}}{2}\right)&=-2\cdot\frac{-\sqrt{3}}{2}=\sqrt{3}.

blockquote.p:
The slope of the curve is \ds\diff{y}{x}. To find \ds\diff{y}{x}, we use the chain rule:
\diff{y}{t}&=\diff{y}{x}\cdot\diff{x}{t}
\diff{}{t}\left\{\cos^2 t\right\}&=\diff{y}{x}\cdot\diff{}{t}\{\sin t\}
-2\cos t \sin t &= \diff{y}{x} \cdot \cos t
\diff{y}{x}&=-2\sin t
So, when t=\dfrac{10\pi}{3}, \diff{y}{x}&=-2\sin\left(\frac{10\pi}{3}\right)=-2\left(-\frac{\sqrt{3}}{2}\right)=\sqrt{3}.
